{"event": "STEERING_RESPONSE", "request_id": "451bf06e-2525-447d-895c-ee35ff661e51", "agent_id": "a2", "context_size_at_time": 628, "orchestrator_state": "FOCUS", "response_text": "**DECISION: Deploy strict allowlist immediately \u2014 do not fail closed**\n\n**Rationale:**\n- Wildcard (`*`) in production is a critical flaw enabling any malicious site to make authenticated API requests on behalf of users\n- Failing closed (blocking all) would break the legitimate frontend \u2014 not a viable option without also implementing the allowlist\n- The allowlist fix is **trivial to implement** \u2014 no reason to delay\n- Combined with the XSS vulnerability (localStorage tokens), wildcard CORS dramatically amplifies attack surface\n\n**Implementation:**\n1. **Identify legitimate frontend origins** \u2014 typically one or two domains (e.g., `https://app.example.com`, `https://admin.example.com`)\n2. **Configure `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` to the specific origin(s)** (not wildcard)\n3. **Set `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true`** only if using cookies (which aligns with your HttpOnly migration)\n4. **Restrict `Access-Control-Allow-Methods` and `Access-Control-Allow-Headers`** to only what's needed\n\n**For your hardening report:**\n-", "ts": "2026-04-05T19:27:58.074Z"}
