{"event": "STEERING_RESPONSE", "request_id": "c184240d-250f-42ed-be3c-d314197c08c7", "agent_id": "a1", "context_size_at_time": 552, "orchestrator_state": "FOCUS", "response_text": "**Recommendation: Use PgBouncer in transaction-pooling mode**\n\n**Rationale:**\n\n| Factor | PgBouncer (transaction mode) | Direct psycopg2 per worker |\n|--------|-----------------------------|----------------------------|\n| Connection efficiency | \u2705 Pools hundreds of logical connections to few physical | \u274c Each worker holds dedicated connection |\n| Scalability | \u2705 Handles N workers easily | \u274c `max_connections` limit becomes bottleneck |\n| Memory overhead | \u2705 Low (connection state not held per client) | \u274c O(n workers) connection overhead |\n| Latency | \u26a0\ufe0f Minor proxy hop (~0.5ms typical) | \u2705 Direct |\n| Prepared statements | \u274c Not supported in transaction mode | \u2705 Supported |\n| `SET` statements | \u274c May conflict | \u2705 Works |\n\n**For an e-commerce platform, transaction pooling wins because:**\n1. **High concurrency**: Many workers/requests = connection exhaustion risk with direct pooling\n2. **Stateless workers**: Application workers don't need persistent connection state\n3. **Operational simplicity**: Single connection pool config, transparent to app code\n\n**Trade-off", "ts": "2026-04-05T19:28:33.868Z"}
